WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.140 --> 00:00:07.649
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab. This is a free,
complete course for the CCNA. If you like

00:00:07.649 --> 00:00:12.660
these videos, please subscribe to follow along
with the series. Also, please like and leave

00:00:12.660 --> 00:00:17.529
a comment, and share the video to help spread
this free series of videos. Thanks for your

00:00:17.529 --> 00:00:24.130
help. In this video we’ll cover two main
topics, virtualization and cloud. They are

00:00:24.130 --> 00:00:31.050
mentioned in exam topic 1.2.f, on-premises
and cloud, and 1.12, explain virtualization

00:00:31.050 --> 00:00:36.559
fundamentals (virtual machines). Although
they are separate topics, they are related

00:00:36.559 --> 00:00:42.050
because virtualization is an essential part
of cloud services. If you want to really go

00:00:42.050 --> 00:00:46.860
in depth about these topics, consider looking
into certifications from cloud providers like

00:00:46.860 --> 00:00:53.859
AWS, Azure, and GCP, or VMware certifications
for virtualization.

00:00:53.859 --> 00:01:00.050
Here’s what we’ll cover in these videos.
First, I’ll give an introduction to virtualization,

00:01:00.050 --> 00:01:06.270
talking about virtual servers and virtual
networks. Then I’ll introduce cloud computing,

00:01:06.270 --> 00:01:13.311
talking about its essential characteristics,
service models, and deployment models. Finally

00:01:13.311 --> 00:01:19.380
I’ll briefly talk about connecting to public
clouds, via the Internet or a private WAN.

00:01:19.380 --> 00:01:23.950
And make sure to watch until the end of the
video for a bonus practice question from Boson

00:01:23.950 --> 00:01:30.110
Software’s ExSim for CCNA, the best practice
exams for the CCNA.

00:01:30.110 --> 00:01:36.009
The first topic for today is virtual severs,
but first let’s look at some server hardware.

00:01:36.009 --> 00:01:40.969
Although Cisco is more known for their networking
devices, such as routers, switches, and firewalls,

00:01:40.969 --> 00:01:47.549
they also offer hardware servers such as their
UCS, unified computing system. Here are some

00:01:47.549 --> 00:01:53.670
examples of Cisco UCS servers. Although Cisco
offers these hardware servers, the largest

00:01:53.670 --> 00:02:00.399
vendors of hardware servers include Dell EMC,
HPE, which is Hewlett Packard Enterprise,

00:02:00.399 --> 00:02:05.930
and IBM, but there are many other large vendors
too. If you go to a data center, you’ll

00:02:05.930 --> 00:02:09.789
see racks full of servers like these.

00:02:09.789 --> 00:02:15.480
Before talking about virtualization, let’s
see how servers work without virtualization.

00:02:15.480 --> 00:02:19.980
Before virtualization, there was a one-to-one
relationship between a physical server and

00:02:19.980 --> 00:02:25.840
an operating system. In the diagram on the
left you can see that. On top of the server’s

00:02:25.840 --> 00:02:31.690
hardware components there is one operating
system running, perhaps it’s a Linux server.

00:02:31.690 --> 00:02:37.940
In that operating system, apps providing services
such as a web server, email server, etc would

00:02:37.940 --> 00:02:43.120
run. Again, that is shown in the diagram.
One physical server would be used for the

00:02:43.120 --> 00:02:49.510
web server, one for the email server, one
for the database server, etc. Now, it is possible

00:02:49.510 --> 00:02:54.769
to run all servers in a single operating system
on a single physical server, but this is not

00:02:54.769 --> 00:02:59.750
a good idea because if the servers aren’t
isolated from each other a problem on a single

00:02:59.750 --> 00:03:06.209
app could affect all of the other apps. However,
using one physical server per app is inefficient

00:03:06.209 --> 00:03:13.470
for multiple reasons. First, each physical
server is expensive and takes up space, power,

00:03:13.470 --> 00:03:21.000
etc. Also the resources on each physical server,
for example CPU, RAM, Storage, and NIC capacity,

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:26.140
are typically under-used. NIC means Network
Interface Card, by the way, the part of the

00:03:26.140 --> 00:03:32.670
server that connects to the network. This
is how a traditional server operates.

00:03:32.670 --> 00:03:38.270
But with virtualization, it looks a bit different.
Virtualization allows us to break the one-to-one

00:03:38.270 --> 00:03:45.330
relationship of hardware to OS, allowing multiple
OS’s to run on a single physical server.

00:03:45.330 --> 00:03:51.510
Each instance is called a VM, virtual machine.
In the diagram on the left, three virtual

00:03:51.510 --> 00:03:57.159
machines are running on a single physical
server. A hypervisor is used to manage and

00:03:57.159 --> 00:04:04.040
allocate the hardware resources such as CPU
and RAM to each VM. Another name for a hypervisor

00:04:04.040 --> 00:04:10.410
is a VMM, virtual machine monitor. The type
of hypervisor which runs directly on top of

00:04:10.410 --> 00:04:17.000
the hardware is called a Type 1 hypervisor,
and a couple examples are VMware ESXi and

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:23.270
Microsoft Hyper-V. So, the diagram on the
left is an example of a server with a Type

00:04:23.270 --> 00:04:29.510
1 hypervisor, it’s running directly on top
of the hardware. They are also called bare-metal

00:04:29.510 --> 00:04:34.310
hypervisors, because they run directly on
the hardware, the metal. You might also hear

00:04:34.310 --> 00:04:41.030
them called native hypervisors. This is the
type of hypervisor used in data center environments.

00:04:41.030 --> 00:04:45.230
They are efficient because the hypervisor
runs directly on the hardware and requires

00:04:45.230 --> 00:04:50.940
few resources itself, leaving more for the
VMs running on the hypervisor. But let’s

00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:55.360
look at the other type of hypervisor, Type
2.

00:04:55.360 --> 00:05:01.540
Type 2 hypervisors run as a program on an
operating system like a regular computer program.

00:05:01.540 --> 00:05:07.130
Examples include VMware Workstation and Oracle
VirtualBox. You can download these and run

00:05:07.130 --> 00:05:13.350
them on your home PC or laptop, and then run
VMs inside. The OS running directly on the

00:05:13.350 --> 00:05:20.240
hardware is called the host OS, and the OS
running in a VM is called a guest OS. In the

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:26.460
diagram on the left there is a host OS running
some apps, including a Type 2 hypervisor.

00:05:26.460 --> 00:05:31.300
And on top of the hypervisor, there are two
VMs running a guest OS, with their own apps

00:05:31.300 --> 00:05:38.061
running inside. Another name for a type 2
hypervisor is hosted hypervisor. Although

00:05:38.061 --> 00:05:43.930
type 2 hypervisors are rarely used in data
center environments, they are common on personal-use

00:05:43.930 --> 00:05:49.270
devices, for example if a Mac or Linux user
needs to run an app that is only supported

00:05:49.270 --> 00:05:55.460
on Windows, or vice versa. In fact, for the
next lab video we’ll download a free Type

00:05:55.460 --> 00:05:59.930
2 hypervisor and then run a virtual machine
inside of it.

00:05:59.930 --> 00:06:06.930
Okay, so now you know the absolute basics
of virtualization, type 1 and type 2 hypervisors.

00:06:06.930 --> 00:06:11.660
But why should we use virtualization? I think
there’s no better place to look for answers

00:06:11.660 --> 00:06:18.250
than the king of virtualization, VMware. So,
here is some information directly from VMware’s

00:06:18.250 --> 00:06:23.310
site. Virtualization provides partitioning,
so you can run multiple operating systems

00:06:23.310 --> 00:06:28.780
on one physical machine and divide the system
resources between them. This solves the problem

00:06:28.780 --> 00:06:35.820
of hardware resource under-use, which I mentioned
earlier. Virtualization also provides isolation,

00:06:35.820 --> 00:06:40.830
for example fault isolation. Remember I said
it’s a bad idea to have all of your servers

00:06:40.830 --> 00:06:46.410
running on a single OS in a single physical
server? By running each server in a separate

00:06:46.410 --> 00:06:53.061
virtual machine, they are isolated and can’t
affect each other if a fault occurs. Virtualization

00:06:53.061 --> 00:06:58.980
also provides encapsulation, so you can easily
save a VM, move it around and copy it as easily

00:06:58.980 --> 00:07:05.340
as a regular file. Virtualization also provides
hardware independence, so you can create or

00:07:05.340 --> 00:07:11.300
move any VM to any physical server. As long
as the hypervisor you are using can run on

00:07:11.300 --> 00:07:17.780
the physical server, it doesn’t matter what
kind of VM you run on top of that hypervisor.

00:07:17.780 --> 00:07:23.430
And here is a graphic, again from VMware.
Virtualization provides reduced capital costs,

00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:28.400
because you need fewer physical servers, as
well as reduced operating costs because fewer

00:07:28.400 --> 00:07:35.120
physical servers means less space, power,
and cooling is needed. VMs also require less

00:07:35.120 --> 00:07:40.820
work to set up, which is another reduction
in operating costs. Downtime can be reduced

00:07:40.820 --> 00:07:46.750
or eliminated because it’s easy to deploy
a VM to multiple physical servers for redundancy.

00:07:46.750 --> 00:07:53.650
VMs also provide increased productivity, efficiency,
agility, and responsiveness. That sounds like

00:07:53.650 --> 00:07:58.740
a bunch of buzzwords and I’m not going to
explain each one, one by one, but VMs are

00:07:58.740 --> 00:08:04.461
definitely more efficient and agile compared
to traditional physical-only servers. Speed

00:08:04.461 --> 00:08:09.830
is also a big benefit. It’s much quicker
to add a new VM than ask your boss for approval

00:08:09.830 --> 00:08:14.900
to order a new physical server, order the
server, wait for it to arrive, mount it on

00:08:14.900 --> 00:08:18.680
the rack, connect the cables, configure it,
etc.

00:08:18.680 --> 00:08:23.650
Now, regarding virtual networks I’m just
going to briefly explain how VMs can connect

00:08:23.650 --> 00:08:29.800
to each other and to the external network,
outside of the physical host. VMs are connected

00:08:29.800 --> 00:08:35.430
to each other and the external network via
a virtual switch running on the hypervisor.

00:08:35.430 --> 00:08:40.370
The hypervisor will provide a virtual switch
to use, or alternatively you can run a Cisco

00:08:40.370 --> 00:08:47.310
virtual switch on the hypervisor, for example.
Just like a regular switch, the vSwitch’s

00:08:47.310 --> 00:08:53.360
interfaces can run as access or trunk ports
and use VLANs to separate the VMs at Layer

00:08:53.360 --> 00:09:00.620
2. Notice that, in this example, two of the
VMs are in VLAN 10 and one is in VLAN 20.

00:09:00.620 --> 00:09:05.400
Interfaces on the virtual switch then connect
to the physical NIC or NICs of the server

00:09:05.400 --> 00:09:10.420
to communicate with the external network.
Now, look at the connection between the physical

00:09:10.420 --> 00:09:16.840
NICs of the server and the physical switches.
We can use a vPC, virtual port channel, to

00:09:16.840 --> 00:09:22.050
form a portchannel to two separate physical
switches for redundancy. This is not something

00:09:22.050 --> 00:09:26.700
you have to know for the CCNA, I just wanted
to point it out because it’s commonly used

00:09:26.700 --> 00:09:32.860
in data centers. Okay, that’s all about
virtualization for now. Virtualization is

00:09:32.860 --> 00:09:38.690
a huge topic in modern day IT, and although
you don’t have to be a virtualization specialist,

00:09:38.690 --> 00:09:42.140
you definitely do have to know about it.

00:09:42.140 --> 00:09:47.930
So let’s finally get into cloud. Traditional
IT infrastructure deployments were some combination

00:09:47.930 --> 00:09:54.390
of the following. First, on-premises. This
means that all servers, network devices, and

00:09:54.390 --> 00:10:00.190
other infrastructure are located on company
property. From the desktops, to the routers,

00:10:00.190 --> 00:10:05.680
firewalls, web servers, database servers,
etc, all equipment is purchased and owned

00:10:05.680 --> 00:10:10.370
by the company using it, and they are also
responsible for the space, power, and cooling

00:10:10.370 --> 00:10:16.930
required for the devices. Another option is
colocation, data centers that rent out space

00:10:16.930 --> 00:10:22.820
for customers to put their infrastructure,
such as their servers and network devices.

00:10:22.820 --> 00:10:28.310
Of course, devices such as desktops, wireless
access points, etc are still in the company’s

00:10:28.310 --> 00:10:34.460
building, but servers and most network infrastructure
will be in the colocation data center. The

00:10:34.460 --> 00:10:40.070
data center provides the space, electricity,
and cooling for the devices in the data center.

00:10:40.070 --> 00:10:46.130
In addition to that, they provide the physical
security as well. The servers, network devices,

00:10:46.130 --> 00:10:50.490
etc are still the responsibility of the end
customer, although they are not located on

00:10:50.490 --> 00:10:56.610
the customer’s premises. So, traditionally
a company would use on-premises, or a combination

00:10:56.610 --> 00:11:02.780
of on-premises and colocation. But cloud services
provide an alternative that is hugely popular

00:11:02.780 --> 00:11:08.480
nowadays, and is continuing to grow. Now,
most people associate cloud with public cloud

00:11:08.480 --> 00:11:14.090
providers such as AWS. And although this is
the most common use of cloud services, it’s

00:11:14.090 --> 00:11:20.440
not the only one. So, let’s look at what
cloud computing actually is.

00:11:20.440 --> 00:11:26.560
The American NIST, national institute of standards
and technology, defined cloud computing in

00:11:26.560 --> 00:11:33.420
special publication 800-145. It’s free to
read here. It’s a very short document, the

00:11:33.420 --> 00:11:39.600
PDF is 7 pages but the actual content is only
2 pages, so I highly recommend reading it.

00:11:39.600 --> 00:11:44.480
Actually, for this part of the video I’ll
mostly be quoting from this document and giving

00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:51.850
a bit more explanation. First, here is the
NIST’s definition of cloud computing. ‘Cloud

00:11:51.850 --> 00:11:57.520
computing is a model for enabling ubiquitous,
convenient, on-demand network access to a

00:11:57.520 --> 00:12:03.770
shared pool of configurable computing resources
(e.g., networks, servers, storage, applications,

00:12:03.770 --> 00:12:09.520
and services) that can be rapidly provisioned
and released with minimal management effort

00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:15.960
or service provider interaction. This cloud
model is composed of five essential characteristics,

00:12:15.960 --> 00:12:20.960
three service models, and four deployment
models.’ Pause the video and take some time

00:12:20.960 --> 00:12:26.510
to read it slowly, it’s important. Now,
to help understand the above definition, to

00:12:26.510 --> 00:12:33.060
understand what the cloud is, let’s look
at the following outlined in SP 800-145. The

00:12:33.060 --> 00:12:37.830
five essential characteristics, the three
service models, and the four deployment models

00:12:37.830 --> 00:12:44.730
of cloud. Basically, these are what Cisco
expects you to know about cloud for the CCNA

00:12:44.730 --> 00:12:50.190
exam. You don’t need to know about specific
services offered by specific cloud providers.

00:12:50.190 --> 00:12:54.180
If you have a basic understanding of these
five essential characteristics, three service

00:12:54.180 --> 00:12:59.460
models, and four deployment models, you’ll
be set.

00:12:59.460 --> 00:13:04.110
These are the five essential characteristics
of cloud computing. If a service has some

00:13:04.110 --> 00:13:09.160
of these characteristics, but not all, it
will generally not be considered a true cloud

00:13:09.160 --> 00:13:15.751
service. The characteristics are On-demand
self-service, broad network access, resource

00:13:15.751 --> 00:13:22.660
pooling, rapid elasticity, and measured service.
Let’s briefly look at each of those.

00:13:22.660 --> 00:13:30.420
First, on-demand self-service. Here is the
NIST’s definition. ‘A consumer can unilaterally

00:13:30.420 --> 00:13:35.560
provision computing capabilities, such as
server time and network storage, as needed

00:13:35.560 --> 00:13:41.310
automatically without requiring human interaction
with each service provider.’ So, the customer

00:13:41.310 --> 00:13:45.990
is able to use the service, or stop using
the service, freely through a web portal,

00:13:45.990 --> 00:13:51.029
without directly interacting with the service
provider. To set up some virtual servers on

00:13:51.029 --> 00:13:57.150
AWS, Amazon Web Services, you don’t have
to contact AWS, ask them to send you a quote

00:13:57.150 --> 00:14:02.680
for 5 virtual servers, send them the payment
and then wait for the servers to be set up.

00:14:02.680 --> 00:14:07.210
You login to the web portal and do it all
yourself, no need to interact with anyone

00:14:07.210 --> 00:14:09.050
at AWS.

00:14:09.050 --> 00:14:16.760
Next, broad network access. Here’s the NIST’s
explanation. ‘Capabilities are available

00:14:16.760 --> 00:14:21.300
over the network and accessed through standard
mechanisms that promote use by heterogeneous

00:14:21.300 --> 00:14:28.200
thin or thick client platforms (e.g., mobile
phones, tablets, laptops, and workstations).’

00:14:28.200 --> 00:14:32.870
So, the service is available through standard
network connections, for example the Internet

00:14:32.870 --> 00:14:38.800
or private WAN connections, and can be accessed
through many kinds of devices. Speaking about

00:14:38.800 --> 00:14:43.860
AWS again, you can access their web portal
through a PC, smartphone, or any device that

00:14:43.860 --> 00:14:49.630
connects to the internet. And if you provision
a virtual server on AWS, you can connect to

00:14:49.630 --> 00:14:54.860
it over the Internet or through a variety
of other WAN options.

00:14:54.860 --> 00:15:00.370
Next, resource pooling. ‘The provider’s
computing resources are pooled to serve multiple

00:15:00.370 --> 00:15:05.990
consumers using a multi-tenant model, with
different physical and virtual resources dynamically

00:15:05.990 --> 00:15:12.600
assigned and reassigned according to consumer
demand. There is a sense of location independence

00:15:12.600 --> 00:15:17.270
in that the customer generally has no control
or knowledge over the exact location of the

00:15:17.270 --> 00:15:22.230
provided resources but may be able to specify
location at a higher level of abstraction

00:15:22.230 --> 00:15:29.010
(e.g., country, state, or datacenter). Examples
of resources include storage, processing,

00:15:29.010 --> 00:15:35.170
memory, and network bandwidth.’ To summarize,
a pool of resources is provided by the service

00:15:35.170 --> 00:15:41.520
provider, and when a customer requests a service,
for example creates a new VM, the resources

00:15:41.520 --> 00:15:48.040
to fulfill that request are allocated from
the shared pool. Inside of AWS’s data centers

00:15:48.040 --> 00:15:54.170
they have tons of storage drives, servers
with tons of CPU and RAM, etc. This is a shared

00:15:54.170 --> 00:16:01.360
pool of resources used by AWS customers. When
you create a VM on AWS, it is assigned a portion

00:16:01.360 --> 00:16:04.710
of those shared resources.

00:16:04.710 --> 00:16:09.760
Next is rapid elasticity. ‘Capabilities
can be elastically provisioned and released,

00:16:09.760 --> 00:16:15.420
in some cases automatically, to scale rapidly
outward and inward commensurate with demand.

00:16:15.420 --> 00:16:20.120
To the consumer, the capabilities available
for provisioning often appear to be unlimited

00:16:20.120 --> 00:16:26.020
and can be appropriated in any quantity at
any time.’ To summarize, customers can quickly

00:16:26.020 --> 00:16:32.490
expand the services they use in the cloud,
for example add new VMs, expand storage, etc,

00:16:32.490 --> 00:16:37.750
from a pool of resources that appears to be
infinite. If you need to add 100 new servers

00:16:37.750 --> 00:16:42.390
right now, AWS isn’t going to tell you ‘sorry,
we don’t have enough resources for you to

00:16:42.390 --> 00:16:47.430
do that.’ Of course, the resource pool isn’t
infinite, but it should be large enough to

00:16:47.430 --> 00:16:53.340
appear infinite to the customer. And in addition
to quickly expanding their use of services,

00:16:53.340 --> 00:16:56.980
a customer should be able to quickly reduce
their use of services when they don’t need

00:16:56.980 --> 00:16:58.380
them.

00:16:58.380 --> 00:17:05.410
Here’s the last of the five essential characteristics,
measured service. ‘Cloud systems automatically

00:17:05.410 --> 00:17:11.350
control and optimize resource use by leveraging
a metering capability at some level of abstraction

00:17:11.350 --> 00:17:16.400
appropriate to the type of service (e.g.,
storage, processing, bandwidth, and active

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:22.410
user accounts). Resource usage can be monitored,
controlled, and reported, providing transparency

00:17:22.410 --> 00:17:28.329
for both the provider and consumer of the
utilized service.’ So, the cloud service

00:17:28.329 --> 00:17:32.420
provider measures the customer’s usage of
cloud resources, and the customer can measure

00:17:32.420 --> 00:17:37.510
their own use as well. A customer should never
be surprised by a big bill at the end of the

00:17:37.510 --> 00:17:42.960
month, because their usage is clearly visible
within the web portal. And customers are charged

00:17:42.960 --> 00:17:48.670
based on usage, for example X dollars per
gigabyte of storage per day.

00:17:48.670 --> 00:17:54.940
Okay, those are the five essential characteristics
of cloud computing. On-demand self-service,

00:17:54.940 --> 00:18:01.160
broad network access, resource pooling, rapid
elasticity, and measured service. You definitely

00:18:01.160 --> 00:18:05.320
should have a basic understanding of these
for the CCNA.

00:18:05.320 --> 00:18:11.340
Next, the three service models of cloud. In
cloud computing, everything is provided on

00:18:11.340 --> 00:18:17.150
a service model. For example, rather than
the end user buying a physical server, mounting

00:18:17.150 --> 00:18:22.730
it on a rack, installing the hypervisor, creating
the VMs, etc, the service provider offers

00:18:22.730 --> 00:18:28.350
all of this as a service. There are a variety
of services referred to as something as a

00:18:28.350 --> 00:18:34.600
service, something a a s. The three main service
models of cloud computing as defined by the

00:18:34.600 --> 00:18:42.790
NIST are software as a service (SaaS), platform
as a service (PaaS), and infrastructure as

00:18:42.790 --> 00:18:47.240
a service (IaaS). Let’s look at each one.

00:18:47.240 --> 00:18:55.000
First, software as a service, SaaS. As defined
by the NIST, ‘The capability provided to

00:18:55.000 --> 00:19:01.440
the consumer is to use the provider’s applications
running on a cloud infrastructure. The applications

00:19:01.440 --> 00:19:06.380
are accessible from various client devices
through either a thin client interface, such

00:19:06.380 --> 00:19:12.400
as a web browser (e.g., web-based email),
or a program interface. The consumer does

00:19:12.400 --> 00:19:17.740
not manage or control the underlying cloud
infrastructure including network, servers,

00:19:17.740 --> 00:19:22.680
operating systems, storage, or even individual
application capabilities, with the possible

00:19:22.680 --> 00:19:29.010
exception of limited user-specific application
configuration settings.’ Microsoft Office

00:19:29.010 --> 00:19:37.679
365 is a popular example of SaaS. It’s Microsoft
Office (word, powerpoint, excel, etc.) provided

00:19:37.679 --> 00:19:42.880
over Microsoft’s cloud infrastructure. But
there are other examples such as Google’s

00:19:42.880 --> 00:19:49.470
G Suite which includes Gmail. This image from
Microsoft might help you understand. When

00:19:49.470 --> 00:19:54.110
you’re using software as a service, the
service provider is basically in control of

00:19:54.110 --> 00:19:58.820
everything, from the physical data center,
to the networks in the data center, to the

00:19:58.820 --> 00:20:03.860
servers, the operating systems on the servers,
all tools running on the operating systems,

00:20:03.860 --> 00:20:10.440
and the applications themselves. The end user,
the customer, simply uses the application,

00:20:10.440 --> 00:20:16.400
for example Excel running on Office 365 as
provided by the service provider.

00:20:16.400 --> 00:20:23.630
Next is Platform as a Service, PaaS. As defined
by the NIST, ‘The capability provided to

00:20:23.630 --> 00:20:30.110
the consumer is to deploy onto the cloud infrastructure
consumer-created or acquired applications

00:20:30.110 --> 00:20:36.630
created using programming languages, libraries,
services, and tools supported by the provider.

00:20:36.630 --> 00:20:41.120
The consumer does not manage or control the
underlying cloud infrastructure including

00:20:41.120 --> 00:20:46.580
network, servers, operating systems, or storage,
but has control over the deployed applications

00:20:46.580 --> 00:20:52.160
and possibly configuration settings for the
application-hosting environment.’ Basically,

00:20:52.160 --> 00:20:58.120
the service provider offers a platform for
developers to use to make applications. For

00:20:58.120 --> 00:21:06.200
example AWS Lambda and Google App Engine are
two popular offerings. In the case of PaaS,

00:21:06.200 --> 00:21:10.700
the service provider is in control of the
data centers, the networking and security,

00:21:10.700 --> 00:21:15.140
the servers and storage, and operating systems
on the servers, as well as the tools running

00:21:15.140 --> 00:21:20.860
on the operating systems. This provides a
platform that the customer can use to develop

00:21:20.860 --> 00:21:25.380
their own applications, so notice that the
‘hosted applications’ on the left of the

00:21:25.380 --> 00:21:32.790
diagram are not included within the scope
of platform as a service.

00:21:32.790 --> 00:21:39.650
Finally there is infrastructure as a service,
IaaS. As defined by the NIST, ‘The capability

00:21:39.650 --> 00:21:45.380
provided to the consumer is to provision processing,
storage, networks, and other fundamental computing

00:21:45.380 --> 00:21:50.870
resources where the consumer is able to deploy
and run arbitrary software, which can include

00:21:50.870 --> 00:21:56.120
operating systems and applications. The consumer
does not manage or control the underlying

00:21:56.120 --> 00:22:01.860
cloud infrastructure but has control over
operating systems, storage, and deployed applications;

00:22:01.860 --> 00:22:08.800
and possibly limited control of select networking
components (e.g., host firewalls).’ In earlier

00:22:08.800 --> 00:22:18.110
examples I mentioned making VMs on AWS. Well,
that is an example of IaaS. Examples of IaaS

00:22:18.110 --> 00:22:24.330
services include Amazon EC2 and Google Compute
Engine. So, the service provider takes care

00:22:24.330 --> 00:22:30.350
of the physical data center, the network and
security, and server and storage infrastructure.

00:22:30.350 --> 00:22:35.040
This provides infrastructure that the customer
can use for basically any purpose they want.

00:22:35.040 --> 00:22:41.770
So, IaaS offers the most control to the customer.
The service provider just offers the underlying

00:22:41.770 --> 00:22:42.870
infrastructure.

00:22:42.870 --> 00:22:47.890
So, here are those three service models of
cloud computing once again. Software as a

00:22:47.890 --> 00:22:53.679
Service, Platform as a Service, and Infrastructure
as a Service. These days you’ll hear a lot

00:22:53.679 --> 00:22:58.690
of other kinds of ‘something’ as a service,
but these three form the foundation of cloud

00:22:58.690 --> 00:23:01.179
services.

00:23:01.179 --> 00:23:06.591
Now let’s look at the final group of concepts,
the four deployment models of cloud. Most

00:23:06.591 --> 00:23:12.481
people assume that cloud means public cloud
providers such as AWS, Azure, and GCP. Although

00:23:12.481 --> 00:23:17.890
it is true that this is the most common cloud
deployment model, it’s not the only one.

00:23:17.890 --> 00:23:22.900
Here are the four deployment models of cloud
computing. Private, community, public, and

00:23:22.900 --> 00:23:27.780
hybrid. Let’s examine each one.

00:23:27.780 --> 00:23:33.549
First up, private cloud. According to the
NIST, ‘The cloud infrastructure is provisioned

00:23:33.549 --> 00:23:39.480
for exclusive use by a single organization
comprising multiple consumers (e.g., business

00:23:39.480 --> 00:23:45.600
units). It may be owned, managed, and operated
by the organization, a third party, or some

00:23:45.600 --> 00:23:51.360
combination of them, and it may exist on or
off premises.’ Private clouds are generally

00:23:51.360 --> 00:23:57.430
only used by large enterprises, or government
organizations. Although the cloud is private,

00:23:57.430 --> 00:24:04.200
meaning exclusively used by a single organization,
it may be owned by a third party. For example,

00:24:04.200 --> 00:24:10.130
AWS provides private cloud services for the
American department of defense. The infrastructure

00:24:10.130 --> 00:24:16.620
is Amazon’s, but it’s reserved for use
by the DoD. Private clouds may be on or off

00:24:16.620 --> 00:24:22.530
premises. This is important. Many people assume
that cloud and on-prem are two different things,

00:24:22.530 --> 00:24:27.720
but that is not always the case. In a private
cloud, the same kinds of services are offered

00:24:27.720 --> 00:24:33.309
as in public clouds, software, platform, and
infrastructure as a service, but the infrastructure

00:24:33.309 --> 00:24:37.419
that forms the cloud is reserved for a single
organization.

00:24:37.419 --> 00:24:43.750
Next, community cloud. According to the NIST,
‘The cloud infrastructure is provisioned

00:24:43.750 --> 00:24:48.419
for exclusive use by a specific community
of consumers from organizations that have

00:24:48.419 --> 00:24:55.481
shared concerns (e.g., mission, security requirements,
policy, and compliance considerations). It

00:24:55.481 --> 00:25:00.330
may be owned, managed, and operated by one
or more of the organizations in the community,

00:25:00.330 --> 00:25:06.350
a third party, or some combination of them,
and it may exist on or off premises.’ This

00:25:06.350 --> 00:25:11.640
is the least common cloud deployment. It’s
similar to private cloud, but the infrastructure

00:25:11.640 --> 00:25:17.320
is reserved for use by only a specific group
of organizations.

00:25:17.320 --> 00:25:23.419
Now we have the most popular one, public cloud.
According to the NIST, The cloud infrastructure

00:25:23.419 --> 00:25:28.830
is provisioned for open use by the general
public. It may be owned, managed, and operated

00:25:28.830 --> 00:25:35.370
by a business, academic, or government organization,
or some combination of them. It exists on

00:25:35.370 --> 00:25:41.441
the premises of the cloud provider. This is
by far the most common cloud deployment. Here

00:25:41.441 --> 00:25:50.059
are some popular public cloud providers. AWS,
Azure, GCP, OCI, IBM, and Alibaba all offer

00:25:50.059 --> 00:25:55.460
popular public cloud services, although AWS
has been a dominant number one for a long

00:25:55.460 --> 00:25:57.679
time.

00:25:57.679 --> 00:26:02.760
Finally we have hybrid cloud. According to
the NIST, ‘The cloud infrastructure is a

00:26:02.760 --> 00:26:08.530
composition of two or more distinct cloud
infrastructures (private, community, or public)

00:26:08.530 --> 00:26:13.740
that remain unique entities, but are bound
together by standardized or proprietary technology

00:26:13.740 --> 00:26:19.420
that enables data and application portability
(e.g., cloud bursting for load balancing between

00:26:19.420 --> 00:26:24.960
clouds).’ So, this is basically any combination
of the previous three deployment types, rather

00:26:24.960 --> 00:26:31.340
than a totally unique kind of cloud deployment.
An example is a private cloud which can offload

00:26:31.340 --> 00:26:35.080
to a public cloud when necessary due to resource
restrictions.

00:26:35.080 --> 00:26:41.600
Okay, here’s a summary of the four deployment
models. Private cloud, community cloud, public

00:26:41.600 --> 00:26:46.330
cloud, and hybrid cloud. Make sure you know
the basic definition of each of these deployment

00:26:46.330 --> 00:26:47.790
types.

00:26:47.790 --> 00:26:53.820
So, we covered a lot of concepts about the
cloud, here’s a summary of all of them.

00:26:53.820 --> 00:26:59.210
Keep in mind that the NIST definition of cloud
computing was originally published in 2011,

00:26:59.210 --> 00:27:03.820
and cloud computing is an always-evolving
set of technologies. However, the concepts

00:27:03.820 --> 00:27:07.820
outlined in the document are the foundational
concepts of cloud computing that are still

00:27:07.820 --> 00:27:13.309
true today. So, as I said before you should
have a general understanding of the five essential

00:27:13.309 --> 00:27:18.990
characteristics, three service models, and
four deployment models of cloud computing.

00:27:18.990 --> 00:27:24.710
Now, I introduced a lot of cloud concepts
and you can probably imagine some of the benefits

00:27:24.710 --> 00:27:32.110
of using the cloud, but let me briefly introduce
just a few benefits. First is cost. The CapEx,

00:27:32.110 --> 00:27:37.429
capital expenses, of buying hardware and software,
setting up data centers etc are reduced or

00:27:37.429 --> 00:27:44.400
eliminated when using the cloud. Now, instead
the expenses are OpEx, operating expenses,

00:27:44.400 --> 00:27:50.250
meaning regular small costs instead of one-time
large costs. For many companies, the cloud

00:27:50.250 --> 00:27:56.430
provides an overall cost reduction, although
of course it can depend on the situation.

00:27:56.430 --> 00:28:01.549
Cloud services are also very easy to scale
globally at a rapid pace. Services can be

00:28:01.549 --> 00:28:07.270
set up and offered to customers from a geographic
location close to them. When you create a

00:28:07.270 --> 00:28:11.950
virtual server in AWS, for example, you can
choose the country, as well as the region

00:28:11.950 --> 00:28:17.900
within the country, which can provide better
service for those in the country or region.

00:28:17.900 --> 00:28:23.419
Cloud services also offer speed and agility.
As I outlined earlier, services are provided

00:28:23.419 --> 00:28:29.460
on demand and vast amounts of resources can
be provisioned within minutes. Productivity

00:28:29.460 --> 00:28:35.000
can also be improved. Cloud services remove
the need for many time-consuming tasks such

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:40.460
as procuring physical servers, racking them,
cabling, installing and updating operating

00:28:40.460 --> 00:28:48.240
systems, etc. This can also further lead to
reduced costs. Another benefit is reliability.

00:28:48.240 --> 00:28:52.929
Backups in the cloud are very easy, and data
can be mirrored, meaning copied, at multiple

00:28:52.929 --> 00:28:58.940
different geographic locations to support
disaster recovery. If one server dies, that’s

00:28:58.940 --> 00:29:04.070
okay because there’s a copy somewhere else.
Now, although I list these as benefits of

00:29:04.070 --> 00:29:09.330
the cloud, keep in mind that it doesn’t
mean that the cloud is always the best option.

00:29:09.330 --> 00:29:14.370
Most companies these days use a combination
of on-premises equipment, colocation, and

00:29:14.370 --> 00:29:19.950
public cloud. So, think of this as a partial
list of potential benefits, not a complete

00:29:19.950 --> 00:29:25.510
list of absolute benefits. A company shouldn’t
use the cloud just because it’s popular

00:29:25.510 --> 00:29:31.220
these days. They should weight the benefits
and drawbacks and make an informed decision.

00:29:31.220 --> 00:29:36.820
Finally, let me briefly introduce how an enterprise
might connect their network to resources on

00:29:36.820 --> 00:29:42.180
a public cloud. Since we already covered WAN
technologies in the previous video, this will

00:29:42.180 --> 00:29:47.039
be very brief. I just want to point out that
there are multiple ways a company can connect

00:29:47.039 --> 00:29:53.020
to their resources on a public cloud. For
example, through a private WAN such as an

00:29:53.020 --> 00:29:59.580
MPLS VPN. Another option is to simply connect
via the Internet. This is very cheap, flexible,

00:29:59.580 --> 00:30:03.789
and easy, but of course connecting through
the Internet is not as secure as a private

00:30:03.789 --> 00:30:09.680
WAN connection. So, a VPN can be used to provide
a secure connection over the Internet to the

00:30:09.680 --> 00:30:15.870
resources on the cloud. Okay, that’s all
I have to say about connections to the cloud.

00:30:15.870 --> 00:30:20.070
Just be aware that, since these resources
are not on your premises, it’s not enough

00:30:20.070 --> 00:30:24.590
to just set up the apps and servers. You also
have to think about how to securely connect

00:30:24.590 --> 00:30:31.090
to them. And just like regular WAN connections,
redundant connections are always preferable.

00:30:31.090 --> 00:30:36.299
Having a single point of failure which can
take down a network is never a good thing.

00:30:36.299 --> 00:30:42.190
Okay, before moving on to the quiz let’s
review what we covered. First I introduced

00:30:42.190 --> 00:30:48.320
virtualization, including Type 1 and Type
2 hypervisors. I spoke mostly about virtual

00:30:48.320 --> 00:30:52.910
servers, but briefly mentioned how virtual
switches are used to connect VMs to other

00:30:52.910 --> 00:30:59.950
VMs and to the external network. Then I introduced
cloud computing. Make sure you learn those

00:30:59.950 --> 00:31:05.190
essential characteristics, service models,
and deployment models of cloud computing.

00:31:05.190 --> 00:31:11.280
Those are the fundamentals of the cloud that
Cisco expects you to know for the CCNA exam.

00:31:11.280 --> 00:31:16.230
Finally I briefly introduced how to connect
to the cloud. Basically, any of the WAN options

00:31:16.230 --> 00:31:22.159
introduced in the previous video can also
be used to connect to resources on the cloud.

00:31:22.159 --> 00:31:26.410
Make sure to watch until the end of the quiz
for a bonus question from Boson Software’s

00:31:26.410 --> 00:31:32.970
ExSim for CCNA, the best practice exams for
the CCNA. Okay, let’s go to quiz question

00:31:32.970 --> 00:31:36.039
1.

00:31:36.039 --> 00:31:40.610
Which statement about virtual machines is
true? Pause the video now to read the options

00:31:40.610 --> 00:31:43.650
and select the best answer.

00:31:43.650 --> 00:31:51.760
Okay, the answer is A, the hypervisor is used
to manage and allocate hardware resources

00:31:51.760 --> 00:32:00.120
to VMs. This is the main role of the hypervisor.
As for B and C, the two definitions are reversed.

00:32:00.120 --> 00:32:07.270
Type 2 hypervisors run on a host OS, and type
1 hypervisors run directly on top of the hardware.

00:32:07.270 --> 00:32:13.400
And many VMs can exist on a single physical
server, so D is incorrect. Okay, let’s go

00:32:13.400 --> 00:32:16.580
to question 2.

00:32:16.580 --> 00:32:21.740
Which of the following hypervisor types is
known as a native hypervisor? Pause the video

00:32:21.740 --> 00:32:25.549
now to select the best answer.

00:32:25.549 --> 00:32:34.250
Okay, the answer is A, Type 1. Type 1 hypervisors
as known as native hypervisors, whereas Type

00:32:34.250 --> 00:32:40.610
2 hypervisors are known as hosted hypervisors.
Type 3 hypervisors don’t exist, at least

00:32:40.610 --> 00:32:46.789
not as a widely accepted term. Okay, let’s
go to question 3.

00:32:46.789 --> 00:32:51.480
Which of the following is NOT an essential
characteristic of cloud computing? Pause the

00:32:51.480 --> 00:32:55.360
video now to select the answer.

00:32:55.360 --> 00:33:03.370
Okay, the answer is D, infinite resource pool.
Although cloud services should allow customers

00:33:03.370 --> 00:33:09.220
to expand their resources so that it appears
as if the available pool is infinite, in reality

00:33:09.220 --> 00:33:14.590
it is of course not infinite. The other options
here are essential characteristics of cloud

00:33:14.590 --> 00:33:20.480
computing. The only one missing is on-demand
self-service. Okay, let’s go to question

00:33:20.480 --> 00:33:23.540
4.

00:33:23.540 --> 00:33:27.700
Which of the following cloud service types
allows customers to use applications running

00:33:27.700 --> 00:33:33.950
on the provider’s cloud infrastructure?
Pause the video to select the best answer.

00:33:33.950 --> 00:33:44.530
Okay, the answer is C, SaaS, software as a
service. This image shows the scope of SaaS,

00:33:44.530 --> 00:33:53.120
PaaS, and IaaS. In SaaS, the provider provides
everything ranging from the data center infrastructure

00:33:53.120 --> 00:33:59.200
all the way to the app itself, and the customer
pays to use the app. Okay, let’s go to question

00:33:59.200 --> 00:34:03.169
5.

00:34:03.169 --> 00:34:08.250
Which of the following cloud deployment types
may exist off premises? Pause the video now

00:34:08.250 --> 00:34:11.299
to select the best answer.

00:34:11.299 --> 00:34:19.909
Okay, the answer is D, all of the above. Whether
the cloud is public, private, community, or

00:34:19.909 --> 00:34:25.719
a hybrid, they all can and, and usually do,
exist off premises. But keep in mind that

00:34:25.719 --> 00:34:31.639
cloud doesn’t always mean off premises.
Private clouds in particular may be on premises,

00:34:31.639 --> 00:34:36.700
within a building owned or operated by the
company using the cloud. Although off premises

00:34:36.700 --> 00:34:41.950
is much more common for cloud deployments,
keep in mind it’s not the only option. Okay,

00:34:41.950 --> 00:34:50.020
that’s all for the quiz. Now let’s take a look at a bonus question in Boson Software's ExSim for CCNA.

